On Mon, Jan 17 2005, Kernel Hacker wrote:
> This patch fixes a potential race condition in mm/page_alloc.c when
> __alloc_pages is called concurrently from interrupt context.

The fix looks correct. The spinlock acquisition before checking the zone
watermarks prevents the race window where a concurrent allocation could
deplete the reserves between the check and the actual allocation.

However, I have a concern about the performance impact. The spinlock is
now held for the entire duration of the zone watermark check, which
could increase lock contention under high memory pressure workloads.

Have you measured the impact with the mmtests benchmark suite? Specifically
the will-it-scale/page_fault[1-4] tests would be informative here.

Also, line 1847 still has the old comment referencing the removed
per-cpu page set fast path -- that should be updated.

Otherwise the change looks good to me. With the performance measurement
and comment update:

